    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="299"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d299">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Advisory Committee/152: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Adviser on Political Relations</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Hornbeck</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-01">May 1,
                            1939</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The papers here attached<note n="34" xml:id="d299fn34">
                        <hi rend="italic">Infra.</hi>
                    </note> were handed to me by the Chinese Ambassador<note n="35"
                        xml:id="d299fn35">Hu Shih.</note> this afternoon.</p>
                <p>The Ambassador said that he was giving me this informally in order to inform us
                    of action which the Chinese Government is contemplating taking at the May
                    session of the Council of the League of Nations. He said that he realized that
                    the hope expressed that the American Government will associate itself with the
                    League in adopting “similar <pb facs="0340" n="336" xml:id="pg_336"/> measures”
                    and will join Great Britain, France and the Soviet Union in making a joint or
                    parallel declaration reaffirming points specified is an expression of wish
                    rather than of expectation. He hoped, however, that the American Government
                    would move in the general direction contemplated and suggested to the powers in
                    the Chinese Government’s outline and expression of request and hope.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>S[<hi rend="smallcaps">tanley</hi>] K. H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >ornbeck</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
